'24:2': [
{sup:1, word:"And", lines:["This chapter primarily reveals the practical living of God&rsquo;s people in oneness with God for the accomplishing of His eternal purpose. The marriage of Isaac was not merely for his human living; it was altogether for the producing of a people, the seed of Abraham, for the fulfillment of God&rsquo;s purpose ({Gen22:17|22:17}). Thus, in the gaining of a wife for Isaac, everything was done according to God&rsquo;s economy to bring forth Christ for the producing of the kingdom of God.","This chapter also presents a rich type of the marriage of Christ, typified by Isaac, and the church, typified by Rebekah."]},
{sup:"2a", word:"servant", vrefs:"Gen. 15:2", lines:["In this account of the marriage of Isaac, Abraham typifies God the Father, the servant typifies God the Spirit, Isaac typifies God the Son, and Rebekah typifies the chosen people of God, who will marry the Son and become His counterpart. The entire New Testament is a record of the Triune God working together to gain a part of the human race to be the bride, the counterpart, of the Son ({Joh3:29|John 3:29}; {2Co11:2|2&nbsp;Cor. 11:2}; {Eph5:25|Eph. 5:25}-{Eph5:32|32}; {Rev19:7|Rev. 19:7}-{Rev19:9|9}; {Rev21:2|21:2}, {Rev21:9|9}-{Rev21:10|10}). In eternity past God the Father had an eternal purpose and made an eternal plan to gain the church as a bride for His Son out of the human race ({Eph3:8|Eph. 3:8}-{Eph3:11|11}). Then, in time, God the Father commissioned God the Spirit to carry out His plan by going to contact the chosen bride and bring her to God the Son to be His counterpart, His wife."]},
],
'24:3': [
{sup:"a", word:"God", vrefs:"Ezra 5:11; Acts 17:24; Gen. 14:19, 22; cf. Gen. 24:7"},
{sup:1, word:"not", lines:["There is no record that God told Abraham not to take a wife for his son from among the Canaanite women (cf. {Deu7:1|Deut. 7:1}-{Deu7:4|4}). Because Abraham lived in oneness with God ({Gen24:40|v. 40a}), he knew God&rsquo;s will and mind and acted in accordance with God&rsquo;s inner feeling (cf. {1Co7:25|1&nbsp;Cor. 7:25} and {1Co7:25^1|note}; {2Co2:10|2&nbsp;Cor. 2:10} and {2Co2:10^3|note 3}; {Phi1:8|Phil. 1:8} and {Phi1:8^1|note})."]},
{sup:"b", word:"daughters", vrefs:"Gen. 26:34-35; 27:46; Deut. 7:3; cf. 2&nbsp;Cor. 6:14"},
],
'24:4': [
{sup:1, word:"relatives", lines:["In typology, the fact that Isaac&rsquo;s bride was taken from Abraham&rsquo;s relatives indicates that the counterpart of Christ must come from Christ&rsquo;s race, not from the angels or from any other creatures ({Gen2:18|2:18}-{Gen2:23|23} and {Gen2:18^1|notes}). Since Christ was incarnated to be a man ({Heb2:14|Heb. 2:14a}), humanity has become His race."]},
{sup:"a", word:"wife", vrefs:"cf. Gen. 28:1-2"},
],
'24:6': [
{sup:1, word:"Be", lines:["Abraham&rsquo;s word to his servant in vv. {Gen24:6|6}-{Gen24:8|8} and {Gen24:40|40} indicates that he lived by faith in the sovereign Lord for the carrying out of His economy in the land of God&rsquo;s promise."]},
],
