'24:53': [
{sup:1, word:"silver", lines:["The gold nose-ring and bracelets ({Gen24:22|v. 22}), the silver and gold jewelry, and the clothing given to Rebekah, along with the precious things given to her brother and her mother, symbolize the unsearchable riches of Christ ({Eph3:8|Eph. 3:8}). The servant testified to Rebekah concerning Isaac&rsquo;s riches, which he inherited from his father (vv. {Gen24:35|35}-{Gen24:36|36}), and gave some of these riches to Rebekah as a foretaste. This caused Rebekah to be attracted to Isaac and made her willing to leave her father&rsquo;s house to be his wife ({Gen24:58|v. 58}) even though she had never seen him. In the same manner the Spirit comes to Christ&rsquo;s believers and testifies to them of the riches of Christ, which He has received from the Father ({Joh16:13|John 16:13}-{Joh16:15|15}), causing them to be attracted to Christ and to love Him, to forsake the world, and to leave their natural relations in the flesh to be joined to Christ ({Mat19:29|Matt. 19:29}), even though they have never seen Him ({1Pe1:8|1&nbsp;Pet. 1:8}). Before Rebekah met Isaac in the good land, she had participated in and enjoyed Isaac&rsquo;s inheritance through the servant&rsquo;s gifts. Likewise, before we meet Christ, we enjoy the gifts of the Spirit as a foretaste of the full taste of His riches ({Heb6:4|Heb. 6:4}; {Rom8:23|Rom. 8:23})."]},
],
