'25:5': [
{sup:"1a", word:"all", vrefs:"Gen. 24:36", lines:["God considered Isaac as Abraham&rsquo;s only son, the unique seed to inherit the promises given by God to Abraham for the fulfillment of His purpose ({Gen22:2|22:2}, {Gen22:12|12}, {Gen22:16|16}, {Gen22:18|18}; {Gen17:19|17:19}; {Gen26:3|26:3}-{Gen26:4|4}). As such, he typifies Christ as the only begotten Son of the Father ({Joh1:14|John 1:14}; {Joh3:16|3:16}), who was given by the Father all that the Father has ({Joh3:35|John 3:35}; {Joh16:15|16:15a}). It was by grace, not by Isaac&rsquo;s effort, that Isaac became the heir of his father&rsquo;s riches."]},
{sup:2, word:"Isaac", lines:["In Genesis the records of Abraham ({Gen12:1|12:1}&mdash;{Gen25:18|25:18}) and Isaac ({Gen21:1|21:1}-{Gen21:8|8}; {Gen22:1|22:1}-{Gen21:24|24}; {Gen24:1|24:1}-{Gen24:67|67}) overlap. Abraham&rsquo;s life reveals that if we would enjoy God&rsquo;s grace and have the full enjoyment of God&rsquo;s riches, we must suffer loss and have our natural life circumcised, cut off. Isaac&rsquo;s life reveals that our suffering to terminate our natural life is for the enjoyment of God&rsquo;s grace. Throughout his entire life Isaac did nothing but enjoy God&rsquo;s rich blessing ({Gen25:11|v. 11}; {Gen26:24|26:24b}), which points to the grace of the New Testament (see {Gen25:11^1|note 11<sup>1</sup>}). Isaac was born in grace ({Gen21:1|21:1}-{Gen21:3|3}; {Gal4:23|Gal. 4:23}), grew up in grace ({Gen21:8|21:8}), and was made an heir of grace ({Gen25:5|v. 5}). In the New Testament, all the called believers are heirs of grace, destined to enjoy God&rsquo;s absolute and unconditional grace ({Eph1:3|Eph. 1:3}, {Eph1:6|6}-{Eph1:8|8}; {Eph2:7|2:7})."]},
],
