'25:26': [
{sup:"1a", word:"holding", vrefs:"Hosea 12:3", lines:["Even while he was still in his mother&rsquo;s womb Jacob was striving to be the firstborn. His desire to be the first corresponded with God&rsquo;s intention that he be the one who would receive the birthright. However, like his grandfather Abraham, Jacob exercised his natural ability and his natural strength to fulfill God&rsquo;s intention and satisfy his desire. Although God had chosen him to be the first, God sovereignly caused Jacob to be born the second so that he might learn that his natural man was altogether unworthy and had to be cut off. Since Jacob&rsquo;s natural man was not qualified, he needed to be transformed.","The record of Jacob&rsquo;s life occupies more than half of the book of Genesis. This long record shows us that the purpose of God in His selecting, predestinating, and calling is to transform sinners into royal sons of God who bear God&rsquo;s image to express Him and exercise God&rsquo;s dominion to represent Him (cf. {Gen1:26|1:26}). God destined Jacob to live a struggling life all his days. Furthermore, God sovereignly arranged every circumstance, situation, and person in Jacob&rsquo;s life and caused them all to work together for Jacob&rsquo;s good, so that He could transform Jacob, a supplanter and a heel holder, into Israel, a prince of God. In particular, God used Jacob&rsquo;s family, including his father, his mother, his brother, his uncle, and his wives and children, to deal with Jacob for his transformation. God&rsquo;s dealing with Jacob is a full picture of the Holy Spirit&rsquo;s discipline and His transforming work in the New Testament believers ({Rom8:28|Rom. 8:28}-{Rom8:29|29}; {Rom12:2|12:2}; {2Co3:18|2&nbsp;Cor. 3:18})."]},
{sup:"2b", word:"Jacob", vrefs:"Gen. 27:36; Matt. 1:2; Acts 7:8", lines:["Meaning supplanter, heel holder."]},
],
