'31:52': [
{sup:1, word:"witness", lines:["The pillar set up here by Jacob was a witness, a testimony. The thought of a pillar as a testimony is seen also in the two pillars (two is the number for a witness, a testimony&mdash;{Mat18:16|Matt. 18:16}; {Luk10:1|Luke 10:1}) set up by Solomon in front of the temple ({1Ki7:21|1&nbsp;Kings 7:21}), and in the church, the house of God, as the pillar that upholds the truth by testifying, manifesting, the truth ({1Ti3:15|1&nbsp;Tim. 3:15}-{1Ti3:16|16}). The three pillars set up by Jacob in chs. {Gen31|31} and {Gen35|35} were three landmarks of Jacob&rsquo;s life. (The pillar set up in {Gen28:18|28:18} was in response to a dream and was not part of Jacob&rsquo;s spiritual experience; hence, it is not considered a landmark in his life. See {Gen35:14^1|note 14<sup>1</sup>} in {Gen35|ch. 35}.) The first pillar, set up at Galeed (vv. {Gen31:45|45}, {Gen31:47|47}), was a testimony of God&rsquo;s sovereign care for him in the first stage of his experience. The second pillar, set up at Bethel ({Gen35:14|35:14}), was a testimony of God&rsquo;s building, God&rsquo;s house, in the second stage. The third pillar, set up on Rachel&rsquo;s grave on the way to Bethlehem ({Gen35:20|35:20}), was a testimony of the death of Jacob&rsquo;s natural choice for the bringing forth of Christ, typified by Benjamin, in the third stage of his experience (see notes {Gen35:18^1|18<sup>1</sup>} and {Gen35:18^3|18<sup>3</sup>} in {Gen35|ch. 35})."]},
],
