'32:24': [
{sup:1, word:"man", lines:["According to {Hos12:4|Hosea 12:4}, this man was the Angel of Jehovah, Christ (see {Exo3:2^1|note 2<sup>1</sup>} in {Exo3|Exo. 3}). The Lord as a man wrestled with Jacob so that He might touch Jacob&rsquo;s natural strength, signified by the socket of Jacob&rsquo;s hip at the thigh muscle (vv. {Gen32:25|25}, {Gen32:32|32}). The Lord&rsquo;s wrestling with Jacob lasted a considerable time, fully exposing how natural Jacob was."]},
{sup:"a", word:"wrestled", vrefs:"Hosea 12:3-4"},
],
'32:25': [
{sup:1, word:"the", lines:["Lit., He."]},
{sup:2, word:"touched", lines:["The touching of the socket of Jacob&rsquo;s hip at the thigh muscle ({Gen32:32|v. 32}), the strongest muscle in the body, signifies the touching of Jacob&rsquo;s natural life, his natural strength. This was the beginning of Jacob&rsquo;s transformation. As {Gen33|ch. 33} shows (see notes {Gen33:4^1|4<sup>1</sup>} and {Gen33:17^1|17<sup>1</sup>} there), after this experience Jacob was still natural. Nevertheless, although there was no change in Jacob&rsquo;s outward living, his natural life, his inward natural strength, had been dealt with by the Lord. This is signified by the fact that Jacob walked with a limp ({Gen32:31|v. 31}). The way of religion is to change man&rsquo;s outward behavior; the way of God in His economy is to touch man&rsquo;s inward life in order to change his inward being."]},
],
