'35:18': [
{sup:1, word:"died", lines:["Rachel was Jacob&rsquo;s natural choice according to his heart&rsquo;s desire ({Gen29:18|29:18}-{Gen29:20|20}). The death of Rachel was the loss of Jacob&rsquo;s natural choice. This was a deep and personal dealing for Jacob. Jacob lost Rachel, but in the process he gained Benjamin, who was a type of Christ. &ldquo;Rachel&rdquo; had to die so that &ldquo;Benjamin&rdquo; could be born. In the same manner, God will eventually take away our natural choice so that we may bring forth Christ for His expression. God&rsquo;s goal is not to make His chosen ones suffer loss; it is to bring forth Christ through them."]},
{sup:2, word:"Ben-oni", lines:["Meaning son of my affliction."]},
{sup:"3a", word:"Benjamin", vrefs:"Gen. 49:27", lines:["Meaning son of the right hand. Benjamin is a type of Christ, who was first Ben-oni, the Son of affliction, from His birth through His human life on earth ({Isa53:3|Isa. 53:3}), but eventually became Benjamin, the Son at the right hand of God, from His resurrection and in His ascension ({Mat26:64|Matt. 26:64}). See {Psa68:27^1|note 27<sup>1</sup>} in {Psa68|Psa. 68}.","Benjamin and Joseph, the two sons born to Jacob by Rachel, are both types of Christ. Although Joseph was born first, in typology he is the continuation of Benjamin, for the record of Joseph&rsquo;s life (chs. {Gen37|37}&mdash;{Gen50|50}) follows the record of Benjamin&rsquo;s birth. Joseph, like Benjamin, typifies the suffering and exalted Christ. During the first part of his life Joseph suffered as the son of affliction, and during the second part he was exalted to the throne at the right hand of Pharaoh ({Gen41:40|41:40}-{Gen41:44|44})."]},
],
