'37:1': [
{sup:1, word:"Jacob", lines:["At this point Jacob was a transformed person, but he was not yet mature. To be transformed is to be metabolically changed in our natural life ({Rom12:2|Rom. 12:2}; {2Co3:18|2&nbsp;Cor. 3:18}); to be mature is to be filled with the divine life that changes us. We may be changed in our natural life (transformed) yet not be filled with the divine life (mature). The last stage of transformation is maturity. Jacob&rsquo;s transformation began at the time God touched him ({Gen32:25|32:25}), and it continued until the end of {Gen36|ch. 36}, when the process of transformation was relatively complete (see {Gen37:3^1|note 3<sup>1</sup>} in {Gen37|ch. 37}). {Gen37:1|Genesis 37:1}&mdash;{Gen43:14|43:14} is a record of the process of Jacob&rsquo;s maturity.","Genesis shows a complete picture of how human beings can be remade and transformed to express God in His image and represent God with His dominion. This book ends as it begins&mdash;with God&rsquo;s image and dominion. The last fourteen chapters indicate that after Jacob had become Israel, he bore the image of God and, through Joseph, exercised the dominion of God. For God&rsquo;s expression and dominion there is the need of maturity. Only a mature life can bear God&rsquo;s image and exercise His dominion."]},
{sup:"a", word:"sojourned", vrefs:"Gen. 17:8"},
],
'37:2': [
{sup:1, word:"Joseph", lines:["In the last fourteen chapters of Genesis the biographies of Jacob and Joseph are blended, indicating that according to spiritual experience, Jacob and Joseph are one person (cf. {Gen12:1^1P2|note 1<sup>1</sup>, par. 2}, in {Gen12|ch. 12} and {Gen25:1^1P2|note 1<sup>1</sup>, par. 2}, in {Gen25|ch. 25}). Joseph is a type of Christ as the One who is altogether perfect, having no defects ({Luk23:4|Luke 23:4}; {2Co5:21|2&nbsp;Cor. 5:21}; {Heb4:15|Heb. 4:15}; {1Pe2:22|1&nbsp;Pet. 2:22}). As such, Joseph represents the reigning aspect of the mature Israel, the constitution of Christ in Jacob&rsquo;s mature nature. As a mature saint constituted of Christ, the perfect One, Jacob reigned through Joseph ({Gen41:39|41:39}-{Gen41:44|44})."]},
{sup:2, word:"shepherding", lines:["Joseph, like Abel, was a shepherd. This signifies the aspect of the constitution of Christ in the mature life that is the shepherding life to care for others ({Joh10:11|John 10:11}; {Joh21:15|21:15}-{Joh21:17|17})."]},
],
'37:3': [
{sup:1, word:"more", lines:["Jacob&rsquo;s preferential love for Joseph indicates that he was not fully transformed but was still living somewhat in the natural life. Jacob&rsquo;s partiality toward Joseph caused him further sufferings, which deeply touched his personal feelings. These final dealings brought him to full maturity for the expression and dominion of God."]},
{sup:"a", word:"old", vrefs:"Gen. 44:20"},
{sup:"b", word:"coat", vrefs:"Gen. 37:23, 31"},
],
'37:5': [
{sup:"1a", word:"dream", vrefs:"Gen. 42:9", lines:["Joseph&rsquo;s two dreams (vv. {Gen37:7|7}-{Gen37:9|9}), both from God, unveiled to him God&rsquo;s divine view concerning the nature, position, function, and goal of God&rsquo;s people on earth. According to their fallen nature, God&rsquo;s people are evil and unclean, but in God&rsquo;s eternal view, His people are sheaves of wheat full of life and heavenly bodies full of light (cf. {Num23:21|Num. 23:21}; {1Ki19:18|1&nbsp;Kings 19:18}; {Rev12:1|Rev. 12:1} and {Rev12:1^1|note}). The reigning aspect of the mature life never condemns God&rsquo;s people (cf. {Gen37:2|v. 2c}). Rather, it shepherds and appreciates them. Joseph&rsquo;s dreams controlled and directed his behavior (cf. {Act26:19|Acts 26:19}). See notes {Gen39:12^1|12<sup>1</sup>} in {Gen39|ch. 39} and {Gen42:9^1|9<sup>1</sup>} in {Gen42|ch. 42}."]},
],
